04363nam a22005775i 9780773581968DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1399979413  a97807735819687 a10.1515/97807735819682doi  a(DE-B1597)657534  a(OCoLC)1245679438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a808/.0322231 aDonaldson, Jeffery, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMissing Link :bThe Evolution of Metaphor and the Metaphor of Evolution /cJeffery Donaldson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b28 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One -- t“Combinatorial Algorithms” -- t“Peyne and Wo”: Metaphor among the Discourses -- tChemistry: Dualities that Enliven -- tDNA and the Three R’s -- tGraceful Errors: The Mutation of Metaphor -- tPossibility Naturalized: The Story of Evolution -- tPart Two -- tMetaphor and Cognition -- tA Word Aside: The Detour that Became a Thoroughfare -- tThe Metaphor of Consciousness -- tMegaphors: The Seeing As Tool -- tNatural and Design Evolution in Culture -- tThe Evolution of Literature -- tSpirit and Its Metaphoric Environment -- t“Til the Ductile Anchor Hold”: The Allowing Conditions of Metaphor -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe look for missing links in the sciences and humanities, but the essential missing link - metaphor - is always in front of us. In Missing Link, Jeffery Donaldson unites literary criticism and evolutionary and cognitive science to show how metaphor has been with us since the beginning of time as a seed in the nature of things. With examples from centuries of poets, critics, philosophers, and scientists, he details how metaphor is a chemistry, an exchange of energies forming and dissolving, and an openness in the spaces between things. He considers the ways in which DNA learns how to liken things that have been, how mutation makes errors and then tries them on, and how evolution is hypothesis - nature's way of "thinking more." The mind is a matrix of relations: neural synapses cascade into ever-changing pathways and patterns. Metaphor is the substance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen. It is the unbroken thread between matter and spirit. Whether offering analysis of a turn of phrase or chemical reaction, Missing Link presents a vision of literature that is also a vision of the cosmos, and vice versa. It enters the debate between evolution and religion, and challenges scientists, literary theorists, and religious advocates to rethink the relations between their disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanities. 0aMetaphor. 0aMétaphore dans la littérature. 0aMétaphore. 0aScience. 0aSciencesxLangage. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358196840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773581968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773581968/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles